<paragraph blockId="3.[264,1325,1532,1884]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Male genitalia. Distiphallus with tubules mostly parallel sided, slightly dilated at apex (
<figureCitation box="[273,374,1572,1598]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 7" captionStartId="3.[264,383,1387,1411]" captionTargetBox="[393,1219,615,1361]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[364,1250,602,1382]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 7. Cerodontha (Dizygomyza) nigrihalterata sp. nov. 1, phallus with hypandrium, ventral view; 2, phallus lateral view; 3, subepandrial sclerite and surstylus (ventral, left); 4, ejaculatory apodeme; 5, epandrium lateral view showing anal projection (ap); 6, head dorsal view; 7, wing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/171389/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Fig. 1, 2</figureCitation>
). Hypandrium broad and rounded (
<figureCitation box="[787,856,1572,1598]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 7" captionStartId="3.[264,383,1387,1411]" captionTargetBox="[393,1219,615,1361]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[364,1250,602,1382]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 7. Cerodontha (Dizygomyza) nigrihalterata sp. nov. 1, phallus with hypandrium, ventral view; 2, phallus lateral view; 3, subepandrial sclerite and surstylus (ventral, left); 4, ejaculatory apodeme; 5, epandrium lateral view showing anal projection (ap); 6, head dorsal view; 7, wing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/171389/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Fig. 
<number box="[842,856,1572,1598]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
). Surstylus with patch of strong bristles at medioventral margin (
<figureCitation box="[561,635,1612,1638]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 7" captionStartId="3.[264,383,1387,1411]" captionTargetBox="[393,1219,615,1361]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[364,1250,602,1382]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 7. Cerodontha (Dizygomyza) nigrihalterata sp. nov. 1, phallus with hypandrium, ventral view; 2, phallus lateral view; 3, subepandrial sclerite and surstylus (ventral, left); 4, ejaculatory apodeme; 5, epandrium lateral view showing anal projection (ap); 6, head dorsal view; 7, wing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/171389/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Fig. 
<number box="[619,635,1612,1638]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
). Ejaculatory apodeme with narrow base and moderately enlarged at apex (
<figureCitation box="[472,545,1652,1678]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 7" captionStartId="3.[264,383,1387,1411]" captionTargetBox="[393,1219,615,1361]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[364,1250,602,1382]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 7. Cerodontha (Dizygomyza) nigrihalterata sp. nov. 1, phallus with hypandrium, ventral view; 2, phallus lateral view; 3, subepandrial sclerite and surstylus (ventral, left); 4, ejaculatory apodeme; 5, epandrium lateral view showing anal projection (ap); 6, head dorsal view; 7, wing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/171389/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Fig. 
<number box="[527,545,1652,1678]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
). Anal projection of epandrium prominent (
<figureCitation box="[1058,1130,1652,1678]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 7" captionStartId="3.[264,383,1387,1411]" captionTargetBox="[393,1219,615,1361]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[364,1250,602,1382]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 7. Cerodontha (Dizygomyza) nigrihalterata sp. nov. 1, phallus with hypandrium, ventral view; 2, phallus lateral view; 3, subepandrial sclerite and surstylus (ventral, left); 4, ejaculatory apodeme; 5, epandrium lateral view showing anal projection (ap); 6, head dorsal view; 7, wing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/171389/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Fig. 
<number box="[1113,1130,1652,1678]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[264,1325,1532,1884]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Derivation of Species Name. The species name refers to the black halteres of this species.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[264,1325,1532,1884]" lastBlockId="4.[264,1323,284,593]" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="5" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Comments. The conspicuously infuscated cells r 
<number box="[891,901,1785,1802]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="1.0">1</number>
and r 
<number box="[972,980,1785,1802]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="3.0">3</number>
+ 
<quantity box="[991,1032,1772,1802]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.016" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" unit="in" value="4.0">4 in</quantity>
the wings and the presence of only one 
<emphasis box="[469,507,1818,1843]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">ors</emphasis>
are unique characters among New World 
<taxonomicName authority="Hendel, 1920" authorityName="Hendel" authorityYear="1920" box="[1006,1149,1818,1843]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Dizygomyza" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1006,1149,1818,1843]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Dizygomyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, the dark halter is also present in 
<taxonomicName authority="Spencer" authorityName="Spencer" box="[619,965,1858,1884]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Cerodontha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inepta">
<emphasis box="[619,841,1858,1883]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Cerodontha inepta</emphasis>
(Spencer)
</taxonomicName>
a species known from 
<collectingCountry box="[1251,1323,1858,1884]" name="Brazil" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Spencer" box="[272,438,284,310]" pageId="4" pageNumber="8" refString="Spencer, K. A. (1963) A synopsis of the Neotropical Agromyzidae (Diptera). Transactions of the Royal Entomological Society of London, 115, 291 - 389." type="journal article" year="1963">
Spencer 
<number box="[375,438,284,310]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" value="1963.0">1963</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). That species was originally placed in the subgenus 
<emphasis box="[1056,1162,284,309]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Poemyza</emphasis>
and was later transferred to 
<taxonomicName authority="Spencer 1966" authorityName="Spencer" authorityYear="1966" box="[431,769,324,350]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Dizygomyza" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[431,574,324,349]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Dizygomyza</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Spencer" box="[591,759,324,350]" pageId="4" pageNumber="8" refString="Spencer, K. A. (1966) Notes on Neotropical Agromyzidae. Papeis Avulsos do Departamento de Zoologia. Secretaria da Agricultura. Sao Paulo, Brasil, 19, 141 - 150." type="journal article" year="1966">
Spencer 
<number box="[696,759,324,350]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" value="1966.0">1966</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. But according to the description of the lunule (high and narrow, upper margin above level of upper 
<emphasis box="[909,943,364,389]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">ori</emphasis>
) it seems that this species does not belong in the subgenus 
<taxonomicName authority="Hendel, 1920" authorityName="Hendel" authorityYear="1920" box="[583,726,404,429]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Dizygomyza" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[583,726,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Dizygomyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Unfortunately the species is known from a female specimen only. Other than the higher lunule, 
<taxonomicName box="[817,1040,444,469]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Cerodontha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inepta">
<emphasis box="[817,1040,444,469]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Cerodontha inepta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs externally from 
<taxonomicName box="[264,633,484,509]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Cerodontha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigrihalterata" subGenus="Dizygomyza">
<emphasis box="[264,633,484,509]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Cerodontha (D.) nigrihalterata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by having 
<number box="[769,784,484,510]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" value="2.0">2</number>
<emphasis box="[793,827,484,509]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">ori</emphasis>
and 
<number box="[887,902,484,510]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" value="3.0">3</number>
<emphasis box="[911,956,484,509]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">ors,</emphasis>
orbital setulae unusually long, last section of CuA 
<number box="[508,518,536,553]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" value="1.0">1</number>
only slightly shorter than penultimate in ratio 
<number box="[1111,1144,524,550]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" value="20.0">20</number>
: 
<number box="[1147,1180,524,550]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" value="22.0">22</number>
, wing only slightly brownish, and stalk of halter yellowish.
</paragraph>
